" âœ… Enable syntax highlighting
syntax on
" ğŸ“Œ This turns on color-coding for code syntax:
"     Keywords, types, functions, strings, comments, etc.
" ğŸ§ª Try it: Open a .c file â€” you'll see 'int' in one color, 'return' in another.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Makes reading and debugging much easier.


" âœ… Show absolute line numbers on the left
set number
" ğŸ“Œ This displays the actual line number of each line.
" ğŸ§ª Try: `gcc main.c -o prog` â†’ If you get "error: line 34", use `34G` to jump there.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Useful for navigating big files and matching compiler errors.


" âœ… Highlight the current line where your cursor is
set cursorline
" ğŸ“Œ Visually emphasizes the row youâ€™re working on.
" ğŸ§ª Try: Move around with `j/k` â€” the active line stays highlighted.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Helps you stay focused in long files or nested logic.


" âœ… Use real tab characters (not spaces)
set noexpandtab
" ğŸ“Œ By default, Vim might insert spaces when you press TAB â€” but 42â€™s Norminette **requires** real tab characters.
" ğŸ§ª Try: Press `<Tab>` in insert mode, then move the cursor over it â†’ it moves as a single character.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Prevents Norminette violations, helps build proper habits.


" âœ… Set how wide the tab character appears
set tabstop=8
" ğŸ“Œ This makes tabs visually take up 8 spaces (default for most terminals, including 42 machines).
" ğŸ§ª Try: Put a few tabs in a line, then count the spacing.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Matches Norminetteâ€™s expectations for indentation layout.


" âœ… Set how many spaces to use for >> (indent) and << (unindent)
set shiftwidth=8
" ğŸ“Œ This controls how far lines shift when you auto-indent with `>>` or unindent with `<<`.
" ğŸ§ª Try: Press `>>` on a line â€” it will move right by 1 tab width.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Keeps your indenting consistent with your tab settings.


" âœ… Automatically indent new lines to match the previous one
set autoindent
" ğŸ“Œ When you press Enter, the new line starts at the same indent level.
" ğŸ§ª Try: Type a function, press Enter â€” it stays aligned.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Saves time and keeps structure visually neat.


" âœ… Smart indenting (for C-style code blocks)
set smartindent
" ğŸ“Œ This adds an extra level of indentation inside curly braces.
" ğŸ§ª Try: Type `{`, press Enter â†’ next line is indented automatically.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Helps you structure loops, functions, and conditionals faster.


" âœ… Donâ€™t wrap long lines to the next line
set nowrap
" ğŸ“Œ Keeps lines horizontal, even if they go beyond the screen.
" ğŸ§ª Try: Create a very long `printf()` and scroll with the arrow keys or `l/h`.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Norminette requires you to manually track line length â€” this mimics that environment.


" âœ… Set file encoding to UTF-8
set encoding=utf-8
" ğŸ“Œ This ensures proper handling of text files (accents, emojis, symbols).
" ğŸ§ª Try: Insert something like `Ã©` or `Ã±` and save â€” it won't break.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Prevents strange behavior when editing or compiling files with comments in multiple languages.


" âœ… Enable incremental search
set incsearch
" ğŸ“Œ As you type `/yourSearch`, it highlights and jumps to the first match live.
" ğŸ§ª Try: Type `/main` â€” it jumps as you type each letter.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Helps you find what you need faster without hitting Enter first.


" âœ… Highlight all matches when searching
set hlsearch
" ğŸ“Œ After pressing Enter from a `/search`, all matches remain highlighted.
" ğŸ§ª Try: `/return`, press Enter â€” every return in the file lights up.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Makes code auditing and debugging much faster.
" ğŸ” Tip: Run `:noh` to clear the highlights.


" âœ… Ignore case in searches...
set ignorecase
" ğŸ“Œ Makes searches case-insensitive unless you use uppercase letters.
" ğŸ§ª Try: `/main` matches "Main", "MAIN", "main" â€” all of them.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Saves time during general searching.


" âœ… ...unless you use a capital letter (Smartcase)
set smartcase
" ğŸ“Œ Now `/Main` will only match "Main", not "main".
" ğŸ¯ Why: Combines best of both worlds â€” loose search when lazy, precise when strict.


" âœ… Highlight matching brackets when the cursor is on one
set showmatch
" ğŸ“Œ When your cursor is on `(`, it briefly jumps to the matching `)`.
" ğŸ§ª Try: Place your cursor on a `{` â€” it blinks to the closing one.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Crucial for debugging nested code blocks.


" âœ… Show what command you're typing at the bottom
set showcmd
" ğŸ“Œ Shows partial commands like `d`, `dd`, `:w` before you finish them.
" ğŸ§ª Try: Press `d`, wait â€” it displays `d` until you complete the motion (`dw`, `dd`, etc).
" ğŸ¯ Why: Gives you feedback while youâ€™re learning Vimâ€™s command language.


" âœ… Show which mode you're in (INSERT, VISUAL, etc.)
set showmode
" ğŸ“Œ Displays your mode at the bottom while editing.
" ğŸ§ª Try: Press `i`, it says `-- INSERT --`. Press `v`, it says `-- VISUAL --`.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Avoids confusion about where your keys will take effect.


" âœ… Always show the status line (bottom bar)
set laststatus=2
" ğŸ“Œ This keeps the bottom info bar always visible.
" ğŸ¯ Why: You can see filename, mode, encoding, and cursor location at all times.


" âœ… Show line/column number of your cursor in the bottom bar
set ruler
" ğŸ“Œ Shows something like `Ln 12, Col 42` in the corner.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Helps monitor line length, location, and match error messages.


" âœ… Ask before closing unsaved files
set confirm
" ğŸ“Œ Prevents accidental quitting â€” itâ€™ll ask "Save changes?" if needed.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Good safety net, especially when tired or stressed.


" âœ… Make Backspace work in all the ways you'd expect
set backspace=indent,eol,start
" ğŸ“Œ This makes backspace delete:
"   - Indentation
"   - End-of-line newlines
"   - Text before where you started editing
" ğŸ¯ Why: Without this, backspace may act weird or fail.


" âœ… Use better tab-completion in command line (e.g., `:e ma<Tab>` â†’ `main.c`)
set wildmenu
set wildmode=longest:full,full
" ğŸ“Œ Adds a nice dropdown-like completion in the command bar.
" ğŸ§ª Try: `:e <Tab>` â€” see the file suggestions.
" ğŸ¯ Why: Helps you autocomplete paths, commands, buffers, etc.


" âœ… Enable mouse support in all modes
set mouse=a
" ğŸ“Œ Lets you use the mouse to:
"   - Move the cursor
"   - Select text
"   - Scroll
" ğŸ¯ Why: Not always needed during exams, but helpful during practice.


